qas.question: How many distinctions in stops do languages like Bengali and Hindi have?

context: Many <b3_0>Indo-Aryan languages<b3_0/> have aspirated stops. Sanskrit, Hindi, Bengali, Marathi, and Gujarati have a <a0_0>four<a0_0/>-way distinction in <b4_0>stops<b4_0/>: voiceless, aspirated, voiced, and <a1_0>breathy-voiced<a1_0/> or voiced aspirated, such as <b7_0>/p pʰ b bʱ/<b7_0/>. <b5_0><b6_0>Punjabi<b5_0/> has lost <a2_0>breathy-voiced consonants<b6_0/><a2_0/>, which resulted in a tone system, and therefore has a distinction between voiceless, aspirated, and voiced: /p pʰ b/.
